-- Japan, South Korea, India, Taiwan, Thailand: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-07-08T22:24:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-08/japan-south-korea-india-taiwan-thailand-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Japan’s Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will
hold a media briefing at 4 p.m.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
stood at 1.14 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 88.40 per dollar at 7:06 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The National Bureau of Statistics will publish the
second-quarter business climate index today. It was at 132.9 in
the March quarter, the highest level since June 2008.  
 The government will sell 20 billion yuan ($2.95 billion) of
182-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.54 percent. The yuan was at 6.7761 per dollar.  
 India: The government will sell 120 billion rupees ($2.6
billion) of bonds maturing in 2015, 2020 and 2032 today.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.60
percent. The rupee was at 46.866.  
 South Korea: The central bank will hold its benchmark rate
at a record low of 2 percent at a meeting today, 10 of the 14
economists surveyed by Bloomberg said. The remainder expect
policy makers to raise borrowing costs.  
 The producer price index will be published by the Bank of
Korea today. Prices paid to producers advanced 4.6 percent from
a year earlier in May, the biggest gain since January 2009.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.52 percent. The won was at 1,209.  
 Thailand: The central bank will sell 70 billion baht ($2.2
billion) of 15-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in December
2019 was 3.29 percent. The baht was at 32.43.  
 Taiwan: The central bank will auction NT$100 billion ($3.1
billion) of 364-day negotiable certificates of deposits today.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent bond maturing March 2020 was
1.42 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar traded at NT$32.185.  
